Duomo (Cathedral)
The park of Villa Olmo and the Cathedral

• [Como Cathedral](/Como_Cathedral): Construction commenced in 1396 on the site of an earlier [Romanesque](/Romanesque_architecture) church, Santa Maria Maggiore. The façade, erected in 1457, features the distinctive [rose window](/Rose_window) and a portal flanked by two Renaissance statues depicting the renowned comaschi [Pliny the Elder](/Pliny_the_Elder) and [Pliny the Younger](/Pliny_the_Younger). The cathedral's construction was finally completed in 1740. The interior is laid out in a [Latin cross](/Latin_cross) plan, with a [Gothic](/Gothic_architecture) nave and two aisles separated by piers. The transept and its adjacent apses, however, are Renaissance in origin. It houses a carved 16th-century choir and tapestries based on cartoons by [Giuseppe Arcimboldi](/Giuseppe_Arcimboldi). The dome is a [rococo](/Rococo) creation by [Filippo Juvarra](/Filippo_Juvarra). Further artistic treasures include 16th–17th-century tapestries and 16th-century paintings by [Bernardino Luini](/Bernardino_Luini) and [Gaudenzio Ferrari](/Gaudenzio_Ferrari).

• [San Fedele](/Basilica_di_San_Fedele_(Como)), a Romanesque church constructed around 1120, believed to have been built over a pre-existing central-plan structure. The original bell tower was reconstructed in modern times. Its most notable feature is the intricately carved medieval decorations on the Door of St. Fedele.

• Sant'Agostino, erected by the [Cistercians](/Cistercians) in the early 14th century, it underwent significant renovations in the 20th century. The interior and adjoining cloister contain 15th–17th-century frescoes, though much of the ornamentation leans towards the [Baroque](/Baroque) style.

• [Basilica of Sant'Abbondio](/Basilica_of_Sant%27Abbondio), a Romanesque edifice consecrated in 1095 by [Pope Urban II](/Pope_Urban_II). The interior, characterized by a nave and four aisles, showcases paintings dating back to the 11th century and frescoes from the 14th century.

• San Carpoforo (11th century, with apse and crypt dating to the 12th century). Tradition holds that it was built upon the foundations of a former temple dedicated to the god [Mercury](/Mercury_(mythology)) to house the remains of [Saint Carpophorus](/Carpophorus,_Exanthus,_Cassius,_Severinus,_Secundus,_and_Licinius) and other local martyrs.

Cathedral as seen at night during the light festival of Como in December 2017

Secular buildings and monuments

• The historic town hall, universally known as the [Broletto](/Broletto).

• [Casa del Fascio](/Casa_del_Fascio_(Como)), widely considered [Giuseppe Terragni](/Giuseppe_Terragni)'s most celebrated work. It has been lauded as an early "landmark of modern European architecture."

• Monumento ai caduti (war memorial) by [Giuseppe Terragni](/Giuseppe_Terragni).

• Teatro Sociale, designed by Giuseppe Cusi and completed in 1813. &#91;42&#93;

• [Villa Olmo](/Villa_Olmo), constructed from 1797 onwards in the neoclassical style by the [Odescalchi](/Odescalchi) family. This villa has hosted a remarkable array of distinguished guests, including Napoleon, [Ugo Foscolo](/Ugo_Foscolo), [Prince Metternich](/Klemens_von_Metternich), Archduke [Franz Ferdinand I](/Archduke_Franz_Ferdinand_of_Austria), and [Giuseppe Garibaldi](/Giuseppe_Garibaldi), among other eminent figures. It now serves as a venue for various exhibitions.

• Monumental Fountain, also referred to as "Volta's Fountain," a tribute to Volta's invention of the battery. This striking structure was designed by architect Carlo Cattaneo and painter [Mario Radice]. It stands at 9 meters (30 feet) tall, composed of a cement assembly of alternating spheres and rings, and is centrally located in Camerlata Square.

• The ancient city walls, a testament to medieval defensive architecture.

• The [Tempio Voltiano](/Tempio_Voltiano), a museum dedicated to the life and work of [Alessandro Volta](/Alessandro_Volta), a distinguished Comasco engineer, physicist, and inventor.

• The [Life Electric](/Life_Electric), a contemporary sculpture crafted by [Daniel Libeskind](/Daniel_Libeskind).

• [Castello Baradello](/Castello_Baradello), a diminutive medieval castle that presides over the town, representing the sole surviving remnant of the fortress originally constructed by [Frederick Barbarossa](/Frederick_I,_Holy_Roman_Emperor) around 1158.

